description:
File: rust/lichen-ipv6/src/lib.rs:791

When responding to Neighbor Solicitation, the code creates the IPv6 header with default hop_limit=64:

```rust
let reply_ip = Ipv6Header::new(next_header::ICMPV6, *local_addr, ip_header.src);
```

But Ipv6Header::new() sets hop_limit to 64:

```rust
pub fn new(next_header: u8, src: Addr, dst: Addr) -> Self {
    Self {
        // ...
        hop_limit: 64,  // Wrong for NDP!
        // ...
    }
}
```

Per RFC 4861 Section 4.4 (Neighbor Advertisement):
- IP Fields: Hop Limit 255

And Section 7.1.2:
- If the source of the solicitation is the unspecified address, the node MUST [...] with an IP Hop Limit of 255.

Impact: Receiving nodes that correctly validate hop_limit=255 will reject our NA responses. This breaks interoperability with RFC-compliant NDP implementations.

Fix: After creating the header, set hop_limit to 255:
```rust
let mut reply_ip = Ipv6Header::new(next_header::ICMPV6, *local_addr, ip_header.src);
reply_ip.hop_limit = 255;
```

Also applies to Echo Reply at line 761 (though RFC 4443 allows any hop limit for Echo Reply, 64 is fine there).
